{"title":"Episodic Transformer for Vision-and-Language Navigation","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Embodied agents following natural-language instructions in household environments must execute long, compositional tasks that require recalling distant past observations and actions. Recurrent policies often struggle to capture such long-term dependencies, leading to failures on long-horizon vision-and-language navigation (VLN) tasks like ALFRED.","method":"Introduce Episodic Transformer (E.T.), a multimodal transformer policy with full-episode observability. A transformer-based language encoder processes the instruction; a visual encoder (ResNet-50 backbone with projection) embeds each observed frame; and a learned action embedding encodes prior actions. These sequences are concatenated and fed to a multimodal transformer with causal attention to prevent access to future timesteps, using positional/temporal encodings. The model predicts actions for all timesteps in a single forward pass with cross-entropy over the full sequence. Ablations show that access to full visual history is critical (16+ past frames approach full-episode results), while more than one past action does not help; compared to an LSTM baseline, E.T. improves task success (e.g., 33.8% vs 23.2% on seen; 3.2% vs 2.4% on unseen)."},{"problem":"Natural human instructions exhibit high linguistic variability, making it hard for agents to learn robust instruction grounding and generalize to unseen environments from limited annotations.","method":"Use synthetic instructions as an intermediate task specification derived from PDDL subgoal actions (e.g., Goto Bed, Put Apple Table), decoupling language variability from visual grounding. (1) Pretrain a seq2seq translator from human to synthetic instructions and transfer the translator’s encoder weights to initialize the agent’s language encoder, outperforming no pretraining and generic BERT pretraining (e.g., 37.6/3.8 vs 33.8/3.2 seen/unseen). (2) Jointly train with additional synthetic demonstrations (≈45K) annotated by subgoal actions, sharing encoders but using separate token tables for human/synthetic text, which yields larger gains than alternative synthetic sources (expert frames or speaker-generated text) and substantially boosts success rates on human-instruction evaluation (e.g., to 38.5/5.4; combining pretraining + joint training reaches 46.6/7.3 on val and 38.42/8.57 on test seen/unseen)."}]}
